1. Basic Log Analysis Commands (Linux)
1Ô∏è‚É£ View logs in real-time
tail -f /var/log/messages


Shows new logs as they appear (live debugging).

2Ô∏è‚É£ View last 50 lines from a log
tail -n 50 /var/log/secure


Used for authentication failures, SSH logs.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Search specific keyword
grep "error" /var/log/messages


Finds all lines containing ‚Äúerror‚Äù.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Case-insensitive search
grep -i "failed" /var/log/secure

5Ô∏è‚É£ Search with line numbers
grep -n "timeout" /var/log/httpd/error_log

6Ô∏è‚É£ View logs page-by-page
less /var/log/messages


Useful for large files.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Monitor file size and growth
du -sh /var/log/*


Find which log file is growing too large.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Find the largest log files
find /var/log -type f -size +100M

9Ô∏è‚É£ Check logs of systemd services
journalctl -u httpd

üîü View today‚Äôs logs
journalctl --since today

üî• 2. Real-Time Scenarios With Commands & Explanation
Scenario 1: Server CPU is high
Check process details
top

Check system logs
grep -i "cpu" /var/log/messages

Check if any service crashed
journalctl -xe

Scenario 2: SSH login failure
Check secure logs
grep -i "failed" /var/log/secure

Check who logged in
last

Block attacker IP
iptables -A INPUT -s <IP> -j DROP

Scenario 3: Disk full because of logs
Find large logs
du -sh /var/log/* | sort -h

Clear old logs
truncate -s 0 /var/log/maillog

Scenario 4: Application not starting
Check app logs
journalctl -fu my-app

Check port usage
ss -tnlp | grep 8080

Check configuration errors
grep -i error /var/log/myapp/error.log

üî• 3. Real Issues & Solutions (With Commands)
Issue 1: Log file growing too fast
Find which file is growing
ls -lh /var/log

Fix: rotate logs

Edit /etc/logrotate.conf

Issue 2: Permission denied while viewing logs
Check permissions
ls -l /var/log/myapp.log

Fix
sudo chmod 640 /var/log/myapp.log
sudo chown root:developers /var/log/myapp.log

Issue 3: Systemd logs full
Check log size
journalctl --disk-usage

Clear logs
journalctl --vacuum-size=500M

Issue 4: Application not writing logs
Check if directory exists
ls -ld /var/log/myapp

Fix
sudo mkdir /var/log/myapp
sudo chmod 755 /var/log/myapp


